article.headline: Jacksonville 58, Lipscomb 49
article.story: JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Aubrey Conerly scored 14 of his game-high 16 points in the final eight minutes, helping Jacksonville rally from a second-half deficit and defeat Lipscomb 58-49 on Saturday. The Dolphins (7-7, 3-4 Atlantic Sun) trailed 39-30 midway through the second half, then got their offense rolling and finished the game on a 28-10 run to post back-to-back wins for the first time in six weeks. Conerly, who tied his season-high in scoring, had seven points in a 15-2 burst that put Jacksonville ahead 45-41, then sealed the win by making five consecutive free throws in the final minute. Cameron Robinson had 10 points and a game-high 10 rebounds for Lipscomb (8-5, 3-3), which missed 15 of its final 16 tries from the field and was held to a season-low in points -- 23.5 below its average entering the game. Lipscomb used a 9-0 run to build a 39-30 lead with 11:15 remaining, but went cold and never recovered. Lipscomb shot just 29.3 percent for the game, and was just 2-for-14 from 3-point range. Jesse Kimbrough had 14 points and David Lee added 12 for Jacksonville.
